elsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"l'Aigle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ernst, Gotthilf.","German: variant of <b>Faigl</b>, a southern short form of <i>Veilchen</i>, the name of the flower violet."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":50,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":59,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert de l'Aigle was born in 1165, in Pevensey, Sussex, England, his father, Richer de l'Aigle II, was 29 and his mother, Odelina, was 26. He married Isabella de Warenne before 1196. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1231, in his hometown, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1165–1231":"1165–1231","–1190":"–1190","–Male":"Surnud","1165–1234":"1165–1234","1196–1216":"1196–1216","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1202–Male":"1202–Surnud","1136–1186":"1136–1186","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","1231":"1231","1186":"1186","1196":"1196","1140":"1140","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1136":"1136","1202":"1202","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","before 1196":"enne 1196","about 1202":"umbes 1202","about 1200":"umbes 1200","about 1196":"umbes 1196","Pontefract, Yorkshire, England":"Pontefract, Yorkshire, England","Pevensey, Sussex, England":"Pevensey, Sussex, England"},"fi":{"1165–1231":"1165–1231","–1190":"–1190","–Male":"Kuollut","1165–1234":"1165–1234","1196–1216":"1196–1216","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1202–Male":"1202–Kuollut","1136–1186":"1136–1186","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","1231":"1231","1186":"1186","1196":"1196","1140":"1140","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1136":"1136","1202":"1202","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","before 1196":"ennen vuotta 1196","about 1202":"noin 1202","about 1200":"noin 1200","about 1196":"noin 1196","Pontefract, Yorkshire, England":"Pontefract, Yorkshire, England","Pevensey, Sussex, England":"Pevensey, Sussex, England"},"fr":{"1165–1231":"1165–1231","–1190":"–1190","–Male":"Décédé","1165–1234":"1165–1234","1196–1216":"1196–1216","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1202–Male":"1202–Décédé","1136–1186":"1136–1186","1140–Female":"1140–Décédée","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","1231":"1231","1186":"1186","1196":"1196","1140":"1140","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1136":"1136","1202":"1202","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","before 1196":"avant 1196","about 1202":"